<TITLE> South Korea rejects Roh call for probe against foe </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Seoul, Dec 17 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - South Korea's justice ministry on Monday rejected President Roh Moo-hyun's call to reopen a fraud probe against the opposition front-runner in presidential elections this week. Former Seoul mayor Lee Myung-bak, who has a 30-point lead in polls ahead of Wednesday's vote, was cleared of allegations of securities fraud earlier this month when prosecutors said they found no evidence of wrongdoing by the candidate. But Roh urged the justice minister on Sunday to consider reopening the probe to clear up lingering doubts following the release of a video from seven years ago in which Lee said he had founded the investment firm at the centre of the fraud investigation. A Justice Ministry official rejected the demand, saying the department instead supported a proposal for an investigation by an independent counsel. "We will be accepting an independent counsel if parliament introduces it," the official said. The ruling United New Democratic Party, whose candidate Chung Dong-young is a distant second in the polls, has proposed an independent counsel to investigate Lee. of Lee, the candidate of the conservative opposition Grand National Party said late on Sunday he would accept an independent counsel if parliament approves one. Analysts said the new video could dent Lee's lead but will not alter his standing as the clear favourite
